If a polypeptide is described as being "linked" to another polypeptide, the linked molecule may or may not include a linker. In certain instances, if a linker serves primarily as a spacer between two molecules, its precise chemical structure is not critical. In certain instances, a linker comprises amino acid residues linked together by peptide bonds, i.e., a linker comprises a peptide. Thus, in certain instances, a linker is a peptide having between 1 and 20 amino acids residues, including all numbers between those endpoints. The amino acid residues used in linkers may be conventional or unconventional amino acid residues. In certain instances, amino acid residues in a linker may be glycosylated and/or derivatized in another manner. In certain instances, the amino acid residues in a linker are selected from glycine, alanine, proline, asparagine, glutamine, and lysine. In certain instances, a linker comprises a majority of amino acid residues that are sterically unhindered, such as glycine and/or alanine. Thus, in certain 73 instances, a linker is selected from a polyglycine (e.g., (Gly)4, (Gly)5), a poly(Gly-Ala), and a polyalanine. Certain exemplary linkers include, but are not limited to:
